\begin{frame}{Dipole antenna}
From the magnetic vector potential formula:
\begin{equation*}
\begin{split}
\vec{A}(\vec{r})&=\frac{\mu_{0}}{4\pi}\int\vec{J}(\vec{r'})\frac{e^{-jkr}}{r}dv'\\
&=\frac{\mu_{0}}{4\pi}\frac{e^{-jkr}}{r}\int_{\frac{-l}{2}}^{\frac{l}{2}}I(z')dz' \hat z\\
&=\frac{\mu_{0}}{4\pi}\frac{e^{-jkr}}{r}I_{0}l\hat z
\end{split}
\end{equation*}
In the form of sphere-coordinate:
\begin{equation*}
\begin{bmatrix}
A_{r}\\
A_{\theta}\\
A_{\phi}\\
\end{bmatrix}
=
\begin{bmatrix}
\sin(\theta)\cos(\phi) && \sin(\theta)\sin(\phi) &&\cos(\theta)\\
\cos(\theta)\cos(\phi) && \cos(\theta)\sin(\phi) && \sin(\theta )\\
-\sin(\phi) && \cos(\phi) && 0 \\
\end{bmatrix}
\begin{bmatrix}
A_{x}\\
A_{y}\\
A_{z}\\
\end{bmatrix}
\end{equation*}
